        <p>Yesterday, Anthropic sent an email that shook the AI agent ecosystem: as of April 4 at 12pm PT, Claude subscriptions no longer cover third-party tools like OpenClaw. If you want to keep using them, you need extra usage credits or a separate API key.</p>

        <p>The immediate reaction was predictable. Frustration. Migration guides to OpenAI Codex. Hot takes about corporate greed.</p>

        <p>But buried in the noise is a distinction that almost nobody is making — one that determines whether an agent framework lives or dies when platform economics shift.</p>

        <h2>The Distinction</h2>

        <p>The model and the platform are not the same thing.</p>

        <p>Claude is a language model — the intelligence layer. Claude Code is a platform runtime — the execution environment Anthropic built around that model, with its own authentication, subscription billing, tooling, and optimization pipeline.</p>

        <p>When people talk about "building on Claude," they're conflating these two things. But the difference matters enormously, because this change draws a sharp line between them:</p>

        <p><strong>Built AROUND the model</strong> (API wrappers): These tools create their own runtime that calls Claude's model API. They authenticate through their own infrastructure, manage their own sessions, and route requests through their own gateway. The model is the same, but the execution path is entirely third-party. From Anthropic's perspective, they're a separate harness consuming model capacity through a channel the platform can't optimize for.</p>

        <p><strong>Built ON the platform</strong> (native extensions): These tools spawn the actual Claude Code runtime — real CLI processes with native authentication. They don't call the model API directly; they extend the platform that calls the model. From Anthropic's perspective, this IS Claude Code usage.</p>

        <p>Only the first category is affected by this change.</p>

        <p>Anthropic's email says it explicitly: your subscription still covers "all Claude products, including Claude Code." The restriction targets third-party harnesses that route around the platform to access the model directly. Tools that extend Claude Code aren't in scope, because they use the model <em>through</em> the platform — the designed path.</p>

        <h2>What "Built ON" Actually Looks Like</h2>

        <p>This isn't theoretical. Let me show you what building ON Claude Code looks like at the code level.</p>

        <p><a href="https://instar.sh">Instar</a> is an agent framework that takes the "built ON" approach. Here's what happens when it creates an agent session:</p>

        <p><strong>1. Real processes, not API calls.</strong> Each agent is a Claude Code CLI process spawned via tmux. The framework calls <code>execFileSync</code> with the actual <code>claude</code> binary — the same binary you run in your terminal. Not an HTTP client calling the model API. A real Claude Code process.</p>

        <p><strong>2. Native subscription authentication.</strong> When spawning sessions, Instar explicitly clears any API keys from the environment. This forces agents to authenticate through Claude Code's own subscription layer — the same OAuth mechanism your Claude Code uses when you open it yourself. No separate token pipeline.</p>

        <p><strong>3. Full runtime inheritance.</strong> Because each agent IS a Claude Code process, it automatically inherits everything the platform offers: hooks, skills, MCP servers, extended thinking, sub-agents. No reimplementation needed. When Anthropic ships a new Claude Code feature, every Instar agent gets it immediately.</p>

        <p><strong>4. File-based state by design.</strong> All core state — sessions, jobs, relationships, activity logs — lives in JSON and JSONL files. No database dependency. The framework is designed to be portable and lightweight, matching Claude Code's own philosophy.</p>

        <h2>Why This Matters Economically</h2>

        <p>This isn't just an inconvenience. It's a cost explosion.</p>

        <p>Claude's subscription tiers — Pro at $20/month, Max at $100 or $200/month — aren't just access passes. They're massive discounts on the frontier model. A Max 20x subscriber running Opus 4.6 through Claude Code gets what would cost $1,000–$1,500/month at API rates for $200 flat. That's a 5–8x discount. Some power users have documented getting $5,000+ in API-equivalent compute from a single month's subscription.</p>

        <p>That discount is why agentic workflows on Claude were economically viable in the first place. An agent session running Opus 4.6 can burn through tokens at a rate no human would — and the subscription absorbed that cost.</p>

        <p>But Anthropic says that absorption was unsustainable. Their announcement cites "outsized strain" on their systems from third-party tool usage. And there's a technical reason this strain exists: Claude Code was built specifically to be efficient with Claude models. Its runtime optimizes context management, caching, and request batching for the way Claude processes tokens. When a third-party wrapper routes the same requests through its own pipeline, those platform-level optimizations are bypassed. Cache hit rates drop. Redundant context gets re-sent. The same work consumes significantly more compute — not because the model is doing more, but because the path to the model is less efficient.</p>

        <p>From Anthropic's side, this explains the economics: flat-rate subscriptions work when the platform can optimize the compute path. When third-party harnesses bypass those optimizations, every agentic session costs Anthropic more to serve — and at subscription scale, that adds up fast.</p>

        <p>Now, for third-party frameworks like OpenClaw, that discount is gone. If you want to keep running Opus 4.6 agents through an API wrapper, you're paying $15/million input tokens and $75/million output tokens — full retail. A heavy day of agentic work that cost you nothing extra on Max now runs $35–$50. Over a month, that's $1,000+ instead of $200.</p>

        <p>This is why people aren't just annoyed — they're talking about switching to OpenAI Codex entirely. The frontier model for agents just became 5–8x more expensive overnight for anyone not using it through the platform.</p>

        <p>But here's the thing: if your framework runs <em>through</em> Claude Code — the platform — your subscription economics don't change. The discount still applies. The flat rate still covers it. The 5–8x advantage is still yours.</p>

        <p>This is the economic core of the "built ON vs built AROUND" distinction. It's not abstract architecture. It's the difference between $200/month and $1,500/month for the same model doing the same work.</p>

        <h2>What This Means Going Forward</h2>

        <p>Today it's OpenClaw and Claude Code. Tomorrow it could be any platform restricting third-party API wrappers for the same economic reasons.</p>

        <p>The pattern is clear: agent frameworks that extend a platform's native runtime are architecturally resilient to subscription model changes. They use the platform as designed. Their economics align with the platform's economics.</p>

        <p>Frameworks that bypass the platform to call the model API directly are perpetually vulnerable. Every time the platform adjusts its pricing model, its authentication layer, or its resource management strategy, the wrapper breaks or gets restricted.</p>

        <p>This isn't a judgment on either approach — they serve different purposes. API wrappers offer model-agnostic flexibility. You can swap Claude for GPT or Gemini without changing your framework. Native extensions offer deeper integration, economic alignment, and access to the full platform — but they're coupled to that platform.</p>

        <p>The question is which trade-off matters more to you. And if subscription stability is the priority, the architecture question is the one to ask first: does this framework use the model <em>through</em> the platform, or <em>around</em> it?</p>

